<h1>Fusion Medical Staffing Review 2026</h1>
<p class="hub-crumb" style="font-family:sans-serif;font-size:0.9em;background:#f0f4ff;border-left:4px solid #3b6cf8;padding:8px 14px;border-radius:0 6px 6px 0;margin:14px 0;">Part of the <a href="travel-nurse-hub-2026.html"><strong>Travel Nursing Hub</strong></a> &mdash; browse every related guide in one place.</p>
<p style="font-size:1.15em;color:#444">Fusion Medical Staffing is the Omaha-based mid-size agency that built its reputation on something unglamorous: being pleasant to work for. No mega-agency bureaucracy, no marketplace app replacing your recruiter &mdash; just a traditional single-recruiter model executed with unusual care. Here's what that actually buys you, and what it doesn't.</p>
<div class="hero-note">
<strong>The one-line version:</strong> Fusion is a culture-first traditional agency &mdash; one recruiter who owns your file, responsive support staff, and solid benefits &mdash; competing on service rather than on having the absolute highest pay package or the biggest job board.
</div>

<h2>The model: one recruiter, done well</h2>
<p>Fusion runs the classic recruiter-centric workflow: you're paired with a single recruiter who learns your specialty, your non-negotiables, and your travel style, then pitches contracts and assembles your submission packets. That model lives or dies on the quality of the individual recruiter, and this is where Fusion's reputation was made. The company invests heavily in internal culture &mdash; it has repeatedly appeared on best-places-to-work lists in its home market &mdash; and the practical consequence for you is lower recruiter turnover. Travelers' most common agency complaint industry-wide is waking up to an email that "your recruiter has left the company"; a shop that retains its people spares you from re-explaining your life every six months.</p>
<p>The trade-off is inherent to the model: your experience is only as good as your assigned human. A great Fusion recruiter is a genuine career advocate; a mediocre one is a bottleneck. If you get a bad match, ask for a reassignment early &mdash; every traditional agency will do this, and the good ones do it without drama.</p>

<h2>Pay: competitive, not chart-topping</h2>
<p>Fusion's packages generally land mid-pack: rarely the highest number you'll be quoted for a given contract, rarely insultingly low. Because it's a traditional agency, the bill rate is not posted &mdash; the recruiter quotes you a package, and there is usually some negotiating room. That makes benchmarking non-optional. Before accepting any Fusion quote, check the same or comparable contracts on a transparent marketplace like <a href="trusted-health-travel-nurse-agency-review-2026.html">Trusted Health</a> or <a href="nomad-health-travel-nurse-agency-review-2026.html">Nomad Health</a>, where the gross is printed on the listing. If Fusion's number is within striking distance and the service is better, many travelers take that trade knowingly &mdash; just make it a decision, not a default.</p>
<div class="warning">
<strong>Stipend math is on you.</strong> Like every agency, Fusion builds packages from a taxable hourly rate plus tax-free stipends. A package that looks bigger can be structured worse &mdash; low taxable rate packages can hurt you on overtime, sick pay, and loan applications. Run every quote through the same blended-rate math; our <a href="travel-nurse-pay-packages-explained.html">pay packages explained</a> guide walks through it line by line.
</div>

<h2>Benefits and the practical details</h2>
<p>Fusion's W-2 package covers the standard set: medical, dental, and vision coverage, a 401(k), licensure and certification reimbursement on qualifying contracts, and travel reimbursement. Nurses consistently mention two practical strengths: a responsive compliance and credentialing team (fast packet turnaround matters when a facility interviews on Tuesday and staffs by Friday), and a housing team that will actually help rather than just pointing you at a stipend. As always, the contract itself governs guaranteed hours, cancellation terms, and missed-shift penalties &mdash; read it, every time, and ask the four pre-signing questions from our <a href="host-healthcare-travel-nurse-agency-review-2026.html">Host Healthcare review</a> regardless of which agency you sign with.</p>

