<h2>The allied dimension most reviews skip</h2>
<p>Fusion staffs far more than nurses: laboratory, radiology, respiratory, and therapy travelers make up a large share of its book. For a travel nurse this matters indirectly &mdash; agencies with diversified allied revenue tend to be more stable through nursing-rate downturns, and less likely to squeeze margins in a panic when nursing bill rates soften. It also makes Fusion a practical answer for travel couples in different disciplines who want one agency handling both contracts.</p>

<h2>Who it fits &mdash; and who it doesn't</h2>
<p>Fusion fits travelers who want a human running point &mdash; especially first- and second-contract nurses who still benefit from coaching, and anyone burned by recruiter churn at bigger shops. It fits travel couples mixing nursing and allied roles. It fits less well for pure rate-maximizers who enjoy playing agencies against each other (the ceiling is usually elsewhere), and for nurses targeting niche or rural markets where the mega-agencies' exclusive facility relationships control the job flow.</p>

<div class="callout">
<strong>Bottom line:</strong> Fusion Medical Staffing is what the traditional agency model looks like when the agency treats its own staff well enough that they stick around to treat you well. Expect mid-pack pay, above-average humans, and a smooth back office. Keep a marketplace profile open for benchmarking, and negotiate every package &mdash; politely, with a competing number in hand.
</div>
